<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="63" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,1238,1694]" pageId="6" pageNumber="63">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,313,1527,1551]" pageId="6" pageNumber="63">Remarks.</emphasis>
The species is close to 
<taxonomicName authority="Collenette" authorityName="Collenette" box="[573,885,1526,1551]" class="Insecta" family="Lymantriidae" genus="Nygmia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="poppaea">
<emphasis box="[573,764,1527,1551]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="63">Nygmia poppaea</emphasis>
Collenette
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Collenette" authorityName="Collenette" box="[938,1166,1526,1551]" class="Insecta" family="Lymantriidae" genus="Nygmia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="venata">
<emphasis box="[938,1045,1528,1551]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="63">N. venata</emphasis>
Collenette
</taxonomicName>
illustrated by 
<bibRefCitation author="Holloway" pageId="6" pageNumber="63" refString="Holloway, J. D. (1999) The Moths of Borneo [Part 5]: family Lymantriidae. Malayan Nature Journal, 53, 1 - 188." type="journal article" year="1999">
Holloway (
<number box="[159,217,1562,1586]" pageId="6" pageNumber="63" value="1999.0">1999</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
in male genitalia characters, but it can be easily differentiated from the latter two by the forewing lacking the broken black fasciae and male genitalia with a smaller aedeagus vesica. It can also be separated from 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Lymantriidae" genus="Nygmia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="poppaea">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="63">N. poppaea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the shorter ventral part of valva, and from 
<taxonomicName box="[724,832,1636,1659]" class="Insecta" family="Lymantriidae" genus="Nygmia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="venata">
<emphasis box="[724,832,1636,1659]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="63">N. venata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the dorsal part of valva without a protrusion at the apex. Female genitalia are illustrated here for the first time.
</paragraph>
